---
title: "Come for the Tool, Stay for the Network"
author: "Chris Dixon"
domain: "cdixon.org"
url: "https://cdixon.org/2015/01/31/come-for-the-tool-stay-for-the-network/"
pubDate: "2015-01-31"
takeaway: "Building a useful single-player tool first is the cleanest way to solve the cold start problem before connecting users into a network."
---

Every cold start problem boils down to a simple dilemma: why would anyone join a network before anyone else is on it? Chris Dixon offers a crisp mental model for solving this by separating single-player utility from multiplayer network effects.

The premise is straightforward. You give users immediate value through a standalone tool so they do not need a crowd to get utility. Instagram gave people free photo filters. Delicious gave people cloud bookmarking. Once users adopt the tool for their own personal workflow, you stitch them together into a social graph. The tool serves as kindling, providing the initial spark long before network density takes hold.

What I appreciate most here is how Dixon frames product defensibility. A good tool gets you out of the gate, but utility alone rarely stops competitors from copying you. Long term retention comes from the connections built on top of it. While not every platform needs a single-player hook, starting with one remains the most reliable way to jumpstart a community.

### What stuck with me

* **Single-player utility precedes multiplayer value:** Give users a reason to show up and stay before expecting them to interact with others.
* **Tools act as kindling:** Standalone utility creates initial traction, but the network layer creates long term retention and defensibility.
* **Free utility beats paid alternatives:** Instagram won early traction partly by offering filter tools for free when competitors charged for them.
* **The playbook is not universal:** Giants like Twitter and Facebook grew without single-player tools, but starting with utility lowers the activation threshold dramatically.
